</p><p>The <code>&agentName;</code> agent puts information into the history
database, which is located in <a href='/History/~'>/History/~</a>, the History
agent's data directory.  Most <a href='/Toolbar/'>Toolbar</a> agents put a
small control bar at the top of each page that refers to the history database.

</p><p>The History control bar looks like this:<br />
<dl>
  <dt> <expand><get agent='History' name='controls' /></expand>
  </dt><dd> 
       <dl compact='compact'>
	 <dt> Hist
	 </dt><dd> -&gt; <a href='/History'>/History</a>, the History Agent's home
	      page  
	 </dd><dt> *
	 </dt><dd> -&gt; <a href='/History/~'>/History/~</a>, the History Agent's
	      data directory.
	 </dd><dt> &year; / &month; /
	 </dt><dd> -&gt; the directories for this year and month.
	 </dd><dt> &day;
	 </dt><dd> -&gt; <a href='/History/~/&year;/&month;/&day;.html'>/History/~/&year;/&month;/&day;.html</a>, the history file for
	      today. 
	 </dd><dt> &time;
	 </dt><dd> -&gt; <a href='/History/~/last.html'>/History/~/last.html</a>, the
	      headers and other information for the most-recently-viewed page.
       </dd></dl>
</dd></dl>

</p><h3>Files:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>History directory: <a href='/History/~'>/History/~</a>
  </li><li>Page info: <a href='/History/~/last.html'>/History/~/last.html</a>
  </li><li>Last link: <a href='/History/~/last.link'>/History/~/last.link</a>
</li></ul>

<p>The ``last link'' file is particularly useful; the following Emacs code
lets you define a key that inserts a link to the last page you visited:

<blockquote><pre><!--  listing doesn't work for some reason  -->
(global-set-key "\C-Cy"   'generic-insert-last-link)
(defun generic-insert-last-link ()
  "Insert a link to the last page visited into the buffer"
  (interactive)
  (insert-file-contents "~/.pia/History/last.link") )
</pre></blockquote>

(Windows users will have to change the file in the last line to
 <code>&usrDIR;/History/last.link</code>).

</p><h3>Directory Format</h3>

The History agent uses a directory hierarchy of the form:

<dl>
  <dt> yyyy/
  </dt><dd> 
       <dl>
	 <dt> mm/
	 </dt><dd> 
	      <dl>
		<dt> dd.html
		</dt><dd> 
	      </dd></dl>
       </dd></dl>
</dd></dl>

The year is always four digits; month and day are always two.  This makes
sorting files by date very easy.  <p>

</p><h3>Agent Act-On Hook</h3>

<blockquote><em>
